Name: Barrier Minefield
Latitude: Well-intentioned attempt by 1 ATF at a physical block to movement—extending from the Horseshoe to the ocean—of men and supplies to VC strongholds in the Long Hai Hills in 1967.Someone didn’t get the memo about minefield security and the end result was a gift to the VC of 5,000 mines that inflicted an estimated 50% of 1 ATF’s casualties in Phuoc Tuy provinceover the next two years.

Name: Barrier Reef
Latitude: Region between the Cambodian border and the canal system connecting Tuyen Nhon (XS2878) and Chau Doc (WS1384), the AO for Op Barrier Reef, an interdiction campaign designed todisable the waterway infiltration network along the southern Cambodian border beginning 2Jan69.

Name: Barrier Reef East

Name: Barrier Strip, The
Latitude: aka The Con Thien Strip, The Trace, The Strip, The Firebreak, Dye Marker, Illinois City, Ryan's Road. 600m wide Rome-plowed strip between Con Thien and Gio Linh secured by 1/4thMarines Apr67. An element of “McNamara’s Line,” aka the Strong Point Obstacle System, a resource-intensive network of physical and high-tech electronic barriers that were supposed tostop infiltration across the DMZ and Laotian panhandle, plus eliminate world hunger. It had an equal chance of achieving either. The entire enterprise was despised as a complete waste ofmanpower and physical resources by the Marines who were tasked with its construction, manning, and maintenance. SPOS was ultimately scrapped.

Name: Batangan Peninsula
Latitude: aka Ba Làng An Peninsula. Notorious VC sanctuary/staging area and offload point for seaborne shipments from the North. It was heavily mined, boobytrapped, perforated with caves, andpopulated with VC-sympathetic civilians. Mũi Ba Tân Gân (Batangan) is a 10 sq-km cape centered at BS7885 (6739-2) but we referred to a much broader area between Quang Ngai andChu Lai from QL-1 to the ocean as the Batangan including Son My ville that encompassed Pinkville and My Lai (4) hamlet. Operation Starlite (1965) took place just north of the cape.

Had it been an ambush rather than an encounter engagement,likely none of Alpha would’ve survived. Grid is Alpha’s final perimeter from detailed overlay.

US 32 KIA, 39 WIA.D/1/5th Marines at Chau Lam (5) [095320]. US 17 KIA, 22 WIA, 1 DOW. Day totals: US 71 KIA, 139 WIA. NVA 476 KIA (BC).The next day NVA were observed collecting their casualties. 1/5th CO Hilgartner declined to fire upon them. For the rest of theday Marines and NVA intermingled without confrontation as they found and removed their dead.

Name: Note: Combined Action Company was abbreviated CAC. Turns out CAC is phonetically similar to a pejorative term in Vietnamese so it was changed to CACO. CACO B-22 would be CAC Bravo, Combined Action Platoon(CAP) 22. This might also be listed as CAP B-22. At some point the system was changed to all numerics. Its format also evolved. Name: Do Xa
Latitude: AT9000-AS9060-BS3060-BT3000. Generally the tri-border region of Kontum (II Corps), Quang Tin, and Quang Ngai (I Corps) provinces. Main VC base area—and at times headquarters(BS1192)—of Military Region 5 (MACV designation Base Area 119) and perennial staging area for attacks on the Quang Ngai, Chu Lai, and Tam Ky regions. This area has been aninsurgent stronghold since the days of the French War. No friendlies here, especially ARVNs. Disused beyond 1968. Also Do Xa War Zone .

Total of 17 WIAs evacuated. Not sure exactly where this happened. Listing is587015, a field position in the sand dunes east of Chu Lai. Journals specifically state "mess hall," suggesting a base area. 1/52nd Inf CPwas at Hill 30. 198th LIB area was Bayonet. Journal later states it occurred at Co B CP so it could have been a field position (listedgrid) and just “chow line” instead of “mess hall.”

Name: Friendly fire
Notes: Battle for Hill 875. 2/503rd Inf (Abn) 19Nov67. Worst incident of the war. USMC A-4 dropped short with two 250 lb’ers near the CPand collection area for WIAs within the battalion 100m diameter LZ/NDP . 42 KHA, 45 WHA. The official USA war history (693) saysthe aircraft was a USAF F-4C that dropped one 750 lb'er. My friend Manny was waiting to be medevaced and came to with a torso inhis lap. I’ve often wondered over the years who was more emotionally brutalized, Manny or the pilot? Check the links for the answer.

Name: Ho Chi Minh Trail
Latitude: aka Route/Highway 559, Trường Sơn Strategic Supply Route, Averell Harriman Memorial Highway (derisively). Collectively the infiltration network supplying the southern insurgencyfrom the North, specifically that portion exiting the DRV panhandle and skirting the DMZ through Laos. The Laotian routes began as foot trails and eventually became a complex andheavily defended system of all-weather roads, supply depots, and support way-stations. According to many sources, this portion of Laos wound up being the most heavily bombed realestate in the history of the planet. "559" commemorated May 1959, when the movement of personnel and supplies from the North began in earnest. That our military was forced to acceptthis strategic liability meant that our ultimate objectives were NEVER in the realm of the obtainable. Trying to conduct war on the cheap is criminal.

Name: Pineapple, The
Latitude: Pineapple groves flank the Oriental River (Song Vam Co Dong) from Hiep Hoa to Luong Hoa then east toward Saigon. The Pineapple Area, Pineapple Batch, Pineapple Grove, PineapplePatch, or just Pineapple sometimes refers to the general plantation area but usually is specific to Base Area 365, bounded in Oct66 by XS6390, 6990, 660865, 6693 with center mass about6690. The Oriental was a principal invasion route from the Parrot’s Beak/Angel’s Wing (Ba Thu region, Cambodia) to Saigon. BA 365 served as a logistics base and staging area forattacking VC/NVA troops only 15km from TSN. The plantation was abandoned in the WWII era and by the sixties was heavily overgrown making movement difficult.

We used the term for the entire area surrounding those locales in southern Batangan including My Lai (4).To Marines in 1968, it was as follows: BS744764 to BS698779 to BS700858 to BS748811. "... completely under VC/NVA control. Theregion contains 80 PCT of the APC target [for pacification] hamlets in Quang Ngai [province]." And not just  under VC control, thepopulation was overwhelmingly supportive of the revolution since the French days. Very dangerous area.

Name: Remuda
Latitude: Maybe the correct name for Ramada at XU (see). According to Bob Kon, B/1/7th Cav, "When we went into Cambodia, our Bn FSB was called LZ Ranch built by D/1/7th Cav. We calledall of our FSBs LZs out of convenience and it sounds nicer, I am guessing.  After Ranch, B/1/7th built LZ Corral and at some point, though I was not on it, our Bn built LZ Bronco. Thus,Remuda continues the horse theme of the first three names." Most report entries are Ramada, Remuda was assumed to be a misspelling. Looks like Ramada might be the misnomer.

Notes: Fortified laagers between FSB Schueller and Mang Yang Pass on QL-19. According to R.J. Smith (see links), 1/69th Armor“strongpoints were manned by either an M-48A3 tank, an M-42 Duster (dual 40mm), or an APC, with an infantry squad. At night wewithdrew to guard the bridges or returned to either LZ Schueller or LZ Action as perimeter defense.” Bridge strongpoints weresometimes manned continuously. Big guns occasionally set up for particular operations. The strongpoint system was an economy offorce measure freeing cav/armor units from resource-intensive convoy escort duties.

Latitude: Presqu'île de Tien Sha (French) on 1954 L509 chart, northeast of Đà Nẵng city. Commonly synonymous with Sơn Trà [Hill 696] Peninsula although Sơn Trà denotes the mountainous massconnected to the mainland by a narrow spit that before circa 1930 was an island at high tide. Tien Sha is inclusive of the panhandle between the Hàn (Đà Nẵng) River and the South ChinaSea including China Beach and Marble Mountain. Tien Sha translates to the Fallen Angel. Tiên Sa-modern.
